\begin{align*}
6a + 3o &= 1.77 \\
2a + 5o &= 1.27 \\
\end{align*}

We are trying to find the cost of each apple and the cost of an orange, so we solve for $a$ and $o$. First, we subtract the first equation from twice the second equation:

\begin{align*}
(2 \times (2a + 5o)) - (6a + 3o) &= 1.27 - 1.77 \\
4a + 10o - 6a - 3o &= -0.5 \\
\Rightarrow -2a + 7o &= -0.5 \\
\Rightarrow 2a - 7o &= 0.5 \\
\end{align*}

We then add this equation to the first equation:

\begin{align*}
2a - 7o &= 0.5 \\
